text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!AccentDiscrimination against Asians in Media%0a%0a:Author: ShahinC%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThe Problem with Apu from The Simpsons%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe following YouTube video demonstrates the racism emanating from the show, The Simpsons, specifically pertaining to Apu. Link to video: https://youtu.be/6J4CEPmdEdI%0a%0aFinally! Some diversity in the media; oh wait, the character is nothing more than a stereotype meant to humiliate and paint the culture with as much negative PR as possible. Got it. %0a%0aThe popular Simpsons character Apu is just one example of accent discrimination in popular media today. On top of all the other stereotypical features that are perpetuated in the show about the character, the accent is perhaps the most easily mocked element of Apu's character. As the author of the New Yorker article states,  "Apu's most distinguishing trait is his accent: theatrically thick, as though someone is luxuriating in all those exotic curled R's and the nasally twang." The character is made fun of for having a thick accent since it falls outside the prescriptivist language and sounds that most non-POC are used to hearing. This portrayal of the character has real negative impacts; it paints all Indians with a broad brush and leads to Indian-Americans being bullied and mocked in society.  Moreover, since it is common to roll the R, (so [ʀ] instead of [ɹ]) when speaking, this leads to them taking accent reduction classes in an attempt to sound more "eloquent" and further erases part of their identity. The dialect that is being made in fun of through Apu is the Hindi dialect. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210503-034038-690720#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Do cartoons really impact people's persepective %0a-> - sathyas%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aOne idea I am curious about is whether people's perspective of Indians is really effected by the cartoon and Apu's accent. Another similar situation is the many instances when legislation attempted to ban violent video games as a means of stopping violence. But do violent video games really cause people to be more violent?%0a%0aI explored on Youtube and google to learn about Indian people's sentiment towards Apu and the stereotypes regarding his character. In the video clip, I found that roughly 2/3 of the people interviewed were not offended or found it funny themselves, and 1/3 seemed mildly offended. They explain that they understand that it is a cartoon and large part of humor is making fun of certain aspects of people. Some even agreed that the depiction of the accent, arranged marriages, and dowries were not totally unrealistic albeit exaggerated.%0a%0aSidharth Bhatia, Mumbai-based founder-editor of The Wire said that, "It (Apu) reflects true American diversity. The controversy about the stereotyping is classist snobbery - Indians in America don't want to be reminded of a certain kind of immigrant from their country - the shop keepers, the taxi drivers, the burger flippers". He explains how the small group of Indian-Americans would rather focus on "Silicon Valley successes, the Wall Street players and the Ivy League products" but in reality there are millions of Apu's in America.%0a%0ahttps://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-44027613%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cJb77ggFgTE%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210503-034038-690720#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: A:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
